{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:46:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:46:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15304"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15304"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.05,0.05,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69015"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"},{"type":"tags","id":"10075"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69015"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe solubility of cholesterol in bile and its relationship to gallstone formation depends on specific biochemical interactions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the solubilisation of cholesterol in bile?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms mixed micelles with bile salts and lecithin","Dissolves directly in aqueous bile solution","Forms complexes with calcium ions","Requires acidic pH for solubility","Binds primarily to albumin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed micelles formed with bile salts and lecithin\u003C/strong\u003E are essential for maintaining cholesterol solubility in bile. Without these amphipathic molecules, cholesterol would precipitate due to its hydrophobic nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissolving directly in aqueous bile solution\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible due to cholesterol\u0027s hydrophobic nature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForming complexes with calcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism of cholesterol solubilisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequiring acidic pH for solubility\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as pH has minimal direct effect on cholesterol solubility\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding primarily to albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant as albumin is not present in significant quantities in bile\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the ratio of cholesterol to bile salts and lecithin becomes too high, cholesterol precipitates as monohydrate crystals, which can lead to gallstone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cholesterol requires bile salts and phospholipids (lecithin) to form mixed micelles for solubilisation in bile","Supersaturated cholesterol crystallises to form cholesterol monohydrate crystals, which can lead to gallstone formation","Excess free cholesterol can damage gallbladder epithelium"],"references":["Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Lammert F, Gurusamy K, Ko CW, Miquel JF, M\u00e9ndez-S\u00e1nchez N, Portincasa P, van Erpecum KJ, van Laarhoven CJ, Wang DQ. Gallstones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Apr 28;2:16024. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.24. PMID: 27121416"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15304"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T20:29:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T20:33:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69015"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji